{"cursor":"2104","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Yanshi' () is a county-level city administered by the prefecture-level city of\nLuoyang in western Henan province, People's Republic of China. Yanshi lies on\nthe Luo River. The main site of the Erlitou culture (1900â1500 BC) was\ndiscovered in the area in 1959. {{cite journal\n  | last1 = Liu | first1 = Li | last2 = Xu | first2 = Hong title = Rethinking\n  | Erlitou: legend, history and Chinese archaeology journal = Antiquity |\n  | volume = 81 | issue = 314 | pages = 886â901 | year = 2007 url =\n  | http://hdl.handle.net/1959.9/58390\n}}\n\nIn 1983, a walled city dating from 1600 BC was found 6km north-east of the\nErlitou site, in Shixianggou Township of Yanshi. This city,\nnow known as Yanshi Shang city (åå¸åå YÇnshÄ« ShÄngchÃ©ng), had an area of nearly\nand featured pottery characteristic of the Erligang culture. {{cite journal\n  | title = Building the chronology of early Chinese history first = Yun Kuen |\n  | last = Lee journal = Asian Perspectives: the Journal of Archaeology for Asia\n  | and the Pacific volume = 41 | issue = 1 | pages = 15â42 | year = 2002 url =\n  | http://scholarspace.manoa.hawaii.edu/handle/10125/17161 doi =\n  | 10.1353/asi.2002.0006\n}} Some scholars identify it with the first Shang Dynasty capital, Xibo,\nwhich according to traditional histories was founded by King Tang after his\ndefeat of the Xia dynasty. {{cite book\n  | last = Schinz | first = Alfred title = The magic square: cities in ancient\n  | China publisher = Edition Axel Menges | year = 1996 isbn = 978-3-930698-02-8\n  | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=qhcRYkz-I3YC\n}} This position was also adopted by the XiaâShangâZhou Chronology\nProject.\n","linknr":307,"url":"Yanshi","recorded":1375079351,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Yanshi&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Yanshi&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php